<dl id="n42068c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n42" href="#n42068c">N42 (VI.B.31)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n42all.htm#n42068c"> 68(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> soul comes / out like / smell of musk / &amp; handed from / angel to angel <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n42068c"><li>FW 191.24 </li><li><a href="../../flex/g/lexg.htm#n42068c">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/g/l39g.htm#n42068c">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n42068c">MS BL 47475-265</ms> </li><li>JJA 47:545 <a name="gd9y" href="../../FF/fdra/gda.htm#gd9y">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/g/gd9.htm#n42068c">Draft: I.7&sect;1.9</a>+/2.9+</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">When a believer is nearly dead, angels of mercy &hellip; say to the soul of the dying man, &ldquo;Come out, O thou who art satisfied with God &hellip;&rdquo; Then the <mark>soul cometh out like the smell of the best musk, so that verily it is handed from one angel to another</mark>, till they bring it to the doors of the celestial regions. <small> Stanley Lane-Poole, <a name="SLPS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SLPS"><cite title="source">The Speeches and Table-Talk of the Prophet Mohammad</cite></a> (1882) 172</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
